  "prompt": "What are microservices?",
  "response": "Microservices is an architectural style and approach to software development where a large application is broken down into smaller, independently deployable services that are loosely coupled and organized around specific business capabilities.\n\nKey characteristics of microservices:\n\n1. Architectural Structure\n- Small, focused services\n- Each service runs as a separate process\n- Independent deployment\n- Loosely coupled components\n\n2. Benefits\n- Scalability\n- Flexibility\n- Easier maintenance\n- Technology diversity\n- Fault isolation\n- Faster development cycles\n\n3. Technical Characteristics\n- Typically use lightweight communication protocols (REST, gRPC)\n- Often containerized (Docker)\n- Independently scalable\n- Can use different programming languages/frameworks\n- Support continuous deployment\n\n4. Communication Patterns\n- Synchronous (HTTP/REST)\n- Asynchronous (Message queues)\n- Event-driven architectures\n\n5. Common Technologies\n- Docker/Kubernetes\n- Service meshes (Istio)\n- API Gateways\n- Messaging systems (Kafka, RabbitMQ)\n\n6. Challenges\n- Complex distributed system\n- Network latency\n- Data consistency\n- Monitoring complexity\n- Service coordination\n\nExample: An e-commerce application might have separate microservices for:\n- User authentication\n- Product catalog\n- Shopping cart\n- Payment processing\n- Order management",
